{
  "id": "incline-friction",
  "title": "Down a ramp: Newton's second law with friction",
  "topic": "dynamics",
  "slug": "incline-friction",
  "scenario": "A block is released from rest on a $\\theta = 30°$ incline with kinetic friction $\\mu = 0.2$. Resolving forces along the slope gives a constant acceleration $a = g(\\sin\\theta - \\mu\\cos\\theta)$ — and crucially, the mass cancels. From there the motion is constant-acceleration kinematics: $v = at$ and $x = \\tfrac12 at^2$, which are just the integrals of that constant $a$. Drag the angle and the friction coefficient and watch all three panels steepen together.",
  "regime": 1,
  "constants": {
    "g": 10.0,
    "theta_deg": 30.0,
    "mu": 0.2
  },
  "initial_conditions": {
    "x0": 0.0,
    "v0": 0.0
  },
  "assumptions": [
    {
      "claim": "A rigid block on a planar incline; kinetic friction acts (the block is already moving), with a constant coefficient $\\mu$ and the normal force $N = mg\\cos\\theta$.",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "$g = 10$ m/s² as a magnitude; the block is released from rest and the incline is long enough that it keeps sliding (we take $\\tan\\theta > \\mu$, so $a > 0$).",
      "kind": "model"
    }
  ],
  "algebra": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "Resolve the forces along the incline (Newton's second law)",
        "latex": "ma = mg\\sin\\theta - \\mu\\,mg\\cos\\theta \\ \\Longrightarrow\\ a = g(\\sin\\theta - \\mu\\cos\\theta)",
        "prose": "Along the slope, gravity pulls the block down with $mg\\sin\\theta$ while kinetic friction resists with $\\mu mg\\cos\\theta$ (the normal force is $mg\\cos\\theta$). The mass cancels, so the acceleration depends only on the angle and the friction coefficient — not on how heavy the block is."
      },
      {
        "label": "Then use the constant-acceleration kinematics",
        "latex": "v = at, \\qquad x = \\tfrac12 at^2, \\qquad v^2 = 2ax",
        "prose": "With $a$ constant and the block released from rest, the speed grows linearly and the distance grows quadratically — the standard formulas."
      }
    ],
    "result": {
      "acceleration": {
        "label": "Acceleration $a = g(\\sin\\theta - \\mu\\cos\\theta)$",
        "unit": "m/s²",
        "symbolic_latex": "g(\\sin\\theta - \\mu\\cos\\theta)",
        "value": 3.267949,
        "display": "3.268"
      },
      "frictionless_accel": {
        "label": "Frictionless acceleration $g\\sin\\theta$",
        "unit": "m/s²",
        "symbolic_latex": "g\\sin\\theta",
        "value": 5.0,
        "display": "5"
      },
      "speed_2s": {
        "label": "Speed after 2 s",
        "unit": "m/s",
        "symbolic_latex": "a\\,t",
        "value": 6.535898,
        "display": "6.536"
      },
      "distance_2s": {
        "label": "Distance in 2 s",
        "unit": "m",
        "symbolic_latex": "\\tfrac12 a t^2",
        "value": 6.535898,
        "display": "6.536"
      }
    }
  },
  "calculus": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "The acceleration is constant — integrate it once for the velocity",
        "latex": "v(t) = \\int_0^t a\\,dt' = at",
        "prose": "Because $a = g(\\sin\\theta - \\mu\\cos\\theta)$ does not change with time, its integral is just $at$. The velocity rises in a straight line — its slope is $a$."
      },
      {
        "label": "Integrate again for the position",
        "latex": "x(t) = \\int_0^t v\\,dt' = \\int_0^t at'\\,dt' = \\tfrac12 at^2",
        "prose": "Integrating the velocity gives the parabola $\\tfrac12 at^2$. The memorized kinematics formula is this integral, already evaluated — a quadrature. The area under the $v$–$t$ line is exactly the distance travelled.",
        "emphasis": true
      },
      {
        "label": "Eliminate time and the velocity–position relation appears",
        "latex": "v^2 = (at)^2 = 2a\\left(\\tfrac12 at^2\\right) = 2ax",
        "prose": "Squaring $v = at$ and substituting $x = \\tfrac12 at^2$ gives $v^2 = 2ax$ with no $t$ — the same identity the algebra course states as a rule. Drag the angle and friction: a steeper slope or less friction means a larger $a$, and all three panels steepen together."
      }
    ]
  },
  "proof": {
    "kind": "equivalence",
    "heading": "The acceleration comes from a free-body diagram; the kinematics are its integrals — algebra is calculus, evaluated.",
    "checked_by": "sympy",
    "holds": true,
    "detail": "check $v = \\int a\\,dt$; check $x = \\int v\\,dt$; show $v^2 = 2ax$; check the $\\mu=0$ limit $g\\sin\\theta$",
    "checks": [
      {
        "key": "velocity_is_integral",
        "claim": "The velocity is the integral of the (constant) acceleration: $v = \\int_0^t a\\,dt' = at$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "position_is_integral",
        "claim": "The position is the integral of the velocity: $x = \\int_0^t v\\,dt' = \\tfrac12 at^2$ — the memorized formula is the quadrature.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "kinematic_identity",
        "claim": "The velocity–position relation falls out: $v^2 = 2ax$ (no time needed).",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      },
      {
        "key": "frictionless_limit",
        "claim": "With no friction ($\\mu = 0$) the acceleration is the bare gravity component $g\\sin\\theta$.",
        "holds": true,
        "tier": "structural"
      }
    ]
  },
