  "misconception": {
    "claim": "A heavier block slides down the ramp faster, because gravity pulls on it harder.",
    "refuted_by": "It does not — two blocks of different mass slide down the same ramp with the *same* acceleration. Gravity does pull harder on the heavier block ($mg\\sin\\theta$ is larger), but that same larger mass is harder to accelerate (the $m$ in $F = ma$), and friction also scales with the normal force $\\mu mg\\cos\\theta$. Every term carries a factor of $m$, so it cancels: $a = g(\\sin\\theta - \\mu\\cos\\theta)$ depends only on the angle and the friction coefficient. This is the same reason all objects fall at the same rate — Galileo's insight, on a ramp."
  },
